# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: slint-ui
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Within computing, **cross-platform software** (also called **multi-platform software**, **platform-agnostic software**, or **platform-independent software**) is computer software that is designed to work in several computing platforms.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] For example, a cross-platform application may run on Linux, macOS and Microsoft Windows.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform software may run on many platforms, or as few as two.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Some frameworks for cross-platform development are Codename One, ArkUI-X, Kivy, Qt, GTK, Flutter, NativeScript, Xamarin, Apache Cordova, Ionic, and React Native.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] A hardware platform can refer to an instruction set architecture.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] For example: ARM or the x86 architecture.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] These machines can run different operating systems.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Smartphones and tablets generally run ARM architecture, these often run Android or iOS and other mobile operating systems.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] A software platform can be either an operating system (OS) or programming environment, though more commonly it is a combination of both.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] An exception is Java, which uses an OS-independent virtual machine (VM) to execute Java bytecode.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] The Java language is typically compiled to run on a VM that is part of the Java platform.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] The Java virtual machine (Java VM, JVM) is a CPU implemented in software, which runs all Java code.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] This enables the same code to run on all systems that implement a JVM.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Java software can be executed by a hardware-based Java processor.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] This is used mostly in embedded systems.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Java code running in the JVM has access to OS-related services, like disk input/output (I/O) and network access, if the appropriate privileges are granted.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] The JVM makes the system calls on behalf of the Java application.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] This lets users to decide the appropriate protection level, depending on an access-control list (ACL).
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] For example, disk and network access is usually enabled for desktop applications, but not for browser-based applets.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] The Java Native Interface (JNI) can also be used to access OS-specific functions, with a loss of portability.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Currently, Java Standard Edition software can run on Microsoft Windows, macOS, several Unix-like OSs, and several real-time operating systems for embedded devices.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] For mobile applications, browser plugins are used for Windows and Mac based devices, and Android has built-in support for Java.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] There are also subsets of Java, such as Java Card or Java Platform, Micro Edition, designed for resource-constrained devices.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] For software to be considered cross-platform, it must function on more than one computer architecture or OS.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Developing such software can be a time-consuming task because different OSs have different application programming interfaces (API).
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Software written for one OS may not automatically work on all architectures that OS supports.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Just because software is written in a popular programming language such as C or C++, it does not mean it will run on all OSs that support that language—or even on different versions of the same OS.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Web applications are typically described as cross-platform because, ideally, they are accessible from any web browser: the browser is the platform.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Web applications generally employ a client–server model, but vary widely in complexity and functionality.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] It can be hard to reconcile the desire for features with the need for compatibility.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Basic web applications perform all or most processing from a stateless server, and pass the result to the client web browser.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] All user interaction with the application consists of simple exchanges of data requests and server responses.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] This type of application was the norm in the early phases of World Wide Web application development.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Such applications follow a simple transaction model, identical to that of serving static web pages.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Today, they are still relatively common, especially where cross-platform compatibility and simplicity are deemed more critical than advanced functionality.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Prominent examples of advanced web applications include the Web interface to Gmail and Google Maps.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Such applications routinely depend on additional features found only in the more recent versions of popular web browsers.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] These features include Ajax, JavaScript, Dynamic HTML, SVG, and other components of rich web applications.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Because of the competing interests of compatibility and functionality, numerous design strategies have emerged.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Many software systems use a layered architecture where platform-dependent code is restricted to the upper- and lowermost layers.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Graceful degradation attempts to provide the same or similar functionality to all users and platforms, while diminishing that functionality to a least common denominator for more limited client browsers.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] For example, a user attempting to use a limited-feature browser to access Gmail may notice that Gmail switches to basic mode, with reduced functionality but still of use.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Some software is maintained in distinct codebases for different (hardware and OS) platforms, with equivalent functionality.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] This requires more effort to maintain the code, but can be worthwhile where the amount of platform-specific code is high.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] This strategy relies on having one codebase that may be compiled to multiple platform-specific formats.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] One technique is conditional compilation.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] With this technique, code that is common to all platforms is not repeated.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Blocks of code that are only relevant to certain platforms are made conditional, so that they are only interpreted or compiled when needed.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Another technique is separation of functionality, which disables functionality not supported by browsers or OSs, while still delivering a complete application to the user.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] (See also: Separation of concerns.) This technique is used in web development where interpreted code (as in scripting languages) can query the platform it is running on to execute different blocks conditionally.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Third-party libraries attempt to simplify cross-platform capability by hiding the complexities of client differentiation behind a single, unified API, at the expense of vendor lock-in.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Responsive web design (RWD) is a Web design approach aimed at crafting the visual layout of sites to provide an optimal viewing experience—easy reading and navigation with a minimum of resizing, panning, and scrolling—across a wide range of devices, from mobile phones to desktop computer monitors.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Little or no platform-specific code is used with this technique.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform applications need much more integration testing.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Some web browsers prohibit installation of different versions on the same machine.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] There are several approaches used to target multiple platforms, but all of them result in software that requires substantial manual effort for testing and maintenance.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Techniques such as full virtualization are sometimes used as a workaround for this problem.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Tools such as the Page Object Model allow cross-platform tests to be scripted so that one test case covers multiple versions of an app.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] If different versions have similar user interfaces, all can be tested with one test case.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Web applications are becoming increasingly popular but many computer users still use traditional application software which does not rely on a client/web-server architecture.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] The distinction between traditional and web applications is not always clear.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Features, installation methods and architectures for web and traditional applications overlap and blur the distinction.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Nevertheless, this simplifying distinction is a common and useful generalization.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Traditional application software has been distributed as binary files, especially executable files.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Executables only support the platform they were built for—which means that a single cross-platform executable could be very bloated with code that never executes on a particular platform.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Instead, generally there is a selection of executables, each built for one platform.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] For software that is distributed as a binary executable, such as that written in C or C++, there must be a software build for each platform, using a toolset that translates—transcompiles—a single codebase into multiple binary executables.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] For example, Firefox, an open-source web browser, is available on Windows, macOS (both PowerPC and x86 through what Apple Inc. calls a Universal binary), Linux, and BSD on multiple computer architectures.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] The four platforms (in this case, Windows, macOS, Linux, and BSD) are separate executable distributions, although they come largely from the same source code.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] In rare cases, executable code built for several platforms is combined into a single executable file called a fat binary.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] The use of different toolsets may not be enough to build a working executables for different platforms.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] In this case, programmers must *port* the source code to the new platform.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] For example, an application such as Firefox, which already runs on Windows on the x86 family, can be modified and re-built to run on Linux on the x86 (and potentially other architectures) as well.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] The multiple versions of the code may be stored as separate codebases, or merged into one codebase.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] An alternative to porting is *cross-platform virtualization*, where applications compiled for one platform can run on another without modification of the source code or binaries.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] As an example, Apple's Rosetta, which is built into Intel-based Macintosh computers, runs applications compiled for the previous generation of Macs that used PowerPC CPUs.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Another example is IBM PowerVM Lx86, which allows Linux/x86 applications to run unmodified on the Linux/Power OS.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] A script can be considered to be cross-platform if its interpreter is available on multiple platforms and the script only uses the facilities built into the language.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] For example, a script written in Python for a Unix-like system will likely run with little or no modification on Windows, because Python also runs on Windows; indeed there are many implementations (e.g.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] The same goes for many of the open-source scripting languages.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Unlike binary executable files, the same script can be used on all computers that have software to interpret the script.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] This is because the script is generally stored in plain text in a text file.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] There may be some trivial issues, such as the representation of a new line character.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform or multi-platform is a term that can also apply to video games released on a range of video game consoles.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Examples of cross-platform games include: *Miner 2049er*, *Tomb Raider: Legend*, *FIFA series*, *NHL series* and *Minecraft*.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Each has been released across a variety of gaming platforms, such as the Wii, PlayStation 3, Xbox 360, personal computers, and mobile devices.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Some platforms are harder to write for than others, requiring more time to develop the video game to the same standard.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] To offset this, a video game may be released on a few platforms first, then later on others.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Typically, this happens when a new gaming system is released, because video game developers need to acquaint themselves with its hardware and software.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Some games may not be cross-platform because of licensing agreements between developers and video game console manufacturers that limit development to one particular console.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] As an example, Disney could create a game with the intention of release on the latest Nintendo and Sony game consoles.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Should Disney license the game with Sony first, it may be required to release the game solely on Sony's console for a short time or indefinitely.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Several developers have implemented ways to play games online while using different platforms.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Psyonix, Epic Games, Microsoft, and Valve all possess technology that allows Xbox 360 and PlayStation 3 gamers to play with PC gamers, leaving the decision of which platform to use to consumers.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] The first game to allow this level of interactivity between PC and console games (Dreamcast with specially produced keyboard and mouse) was *Quake 3*.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Games that feature cross-platform online play include *Rocket League*, *Final Fantasy XIV*, *Street Fighter V*, *Killer Instinct*, *Paragon* and *Fable Fortune,* and *Minecraft* with its Better Together update on Windows 10, VR editions, Pocket Edition and Xbox One.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform programming is the practice of deliberately writing software to work on more than one platform.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] There are different ways to write a cross-platform application.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] One approach is to create multiple versions of the same software in different *source trees*—in other words, the Microsoft Windows version of an application might have one set of source code files and the Macintosh version another, while a FOSS *nix system might have a third.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] While this is straightforward, compared to developing for only one platform it can cost much more to pay a larger team or release products more slowly.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] It can also result in more bugs to be tracked and fixed.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Another approach is to use software that hides the differences between the platforms.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] This abstraction layer insulates the application from the platform.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Such applications are *platform agnostic*.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Applications that run on the JVM are built this way.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Some applications mix various methods of cross-platform programming to create the final application.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] An example is the Firefox web browser, which uses abstraction to build some of the lower-level components, with separate source subtrees for implementing platform-specific features (like the GUI), and the implementation of more than one scripting language to ease software portability.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Firefox implements XUL, CSS and JavaScript for extending the browser, in addition to classic Netscape-style browser plugins.
[src:slint-ui/cross-platform-software] Much of the browser itself is written in XUL, CSS, and JavaScript.
[src:slint-ui/declarative-programming] In computer science, **declarative programming** is a programming paradigm that expresses the logic of a computation without fully describing its control flow.
[src:slint-ui/declarative-programming] This is in contrast with imperative programming, which implements algorithms in explicit steps.
[src:slint-ui/declarative-programming] Declarative programming may consider programs as theories of a formal logic, and computations as deductions in that logical theory.
[src:slint-ui/declarative-programming] Declarative programming at times simplifies the writing of parallel programs.
[src:slint-ui/declarative-programming] Common declarative language paradigms include logic programming (e.g., Prolog, Datalog, answer set programming), and algebraic modeling systems.
[src:slint-ui/declarative-programming] Declarative programming is often defined as any style of programming that is not imperative.
[src:slint-ui/declarative-programming] A number of other common definitions attempt to define it by simply contrasting it with imperative programming.
[src:slint-ui/declarative-programming] These definitions overlap substantially.
[src:slint-ui/declarative-programming] Declarative programming is a non-imperative style of programming in which programs describe their desired results without explicitly listing commands or steps that must be performed.
[src:slint-ui/declarative-programming] Logic programming languages are characterized by a mostly declarative programming style.
[src:slint-ui/declarative-programming] In logic programming, programs consist of sentences expressed in logical form, and computation uses those sentences to solve problems, which are also expressed in logical form.
[src:slint-ui/declarative-programming] In a pure functional language, such as Haskell, all functions are without side effects, and state changes are only represented as functions that transform the state, which is explicitly represented as a first-class object in the program.
[src:slint-ui/declarative-programming] Although pure functional languages are non-imperative, they often provide a facility for describing the effect of a function as a series of steps.
[src:slint-ui/declarative-programming] Other functional languages, such as Lisp, OCaml and Erlang, support a mixture of procedural and functional programming.
[src:slint-ui/declarative-programming] Some logic programming languages, such as Prolog, and database query languages, such as SQL, while declarative in principle, also support a procedural style of programming.
[src:slint-ui/declarative-programming] Declarative programming is an umbrella term that includes a number of better-known programming paradigms.
[src:slint-ui/declarative-programming] Constraint programming states relations between variables in the form of constraints that specify the properties of the target solution.
[src:slint-ui/declarative-programming] The set of constraints is solved by giving a value to each variable so that the solution is consistent with the maximum number of constraints.
[src:slint-ui/declarative-programming] Constraint programming often complements other paradigms: functional, logical, or even imperative programming.
[src:slint-ui/declarative-programming] Makefiles, for example, specify dependencies in a declarative fashion, but include an imperative list of actions to take as well.
[src:slint-ui/declarative-programming] Similarly, yacc specifies a context free grammar declaratively, but includes code snippets from a host language, which is usually imperative (such as C).
[src:slint-ui/declarative-programming] Logic programming languages, such as Prolog, Datalog and answer set programming, compute by proving that a goal is a logical consequence of the program, or by showing that the goal is true in a model defined by the program.
[src:slint-ui/declarative-programming] Prolog computes by reducing goals to subgoals, top-down using backward reasoning, whereas most Datalog systems compute bottom-up using forward reasoning.
[src:slint-ui/declarative-programming] Answer set programs typically use SAT solvers to generate a model of the program.
[src:slint-ui/declarative-programming] Models, or mathematical representations, of physical systems may be implemented in computer code that is declarative.
[src:slint-ui/declarative-programming] The code contains a number of equations, not imperative assignments, that describe ("declare") the behavioral relationships.
[src:slint-ui/declarative-programming] When a model is expressed in this formalism, a computer is able to perform algebraic manipulations to best formulate the solution algorithm.
[src:slint-ui/declarative-programming] The mathematical causality is typically imposed at the boundaries of the physical system, while the behavioral description of the system itself is declarative or acausal.
[src:slint-ui/declarative-programming] Declarative modeling languages and environments include Analytica, Modelica and Simile.
[src:slint-ui/declarative-programming] Prolog (1972) stands for "PROgramming in LOGic." It was developed for natural language question answering, using SL resolution both to deduce answers to queries and to parse and generate natural language sentences.
[src:slint-ui/declarative-programming] The building blocks of a Prolog program are *facts* and *rules*.
[src:slint-ui/declarative-programming] Given this program, the query `eat(tom,jerry)` succeeds, while `eat(jerry,tom)` fails.
[src:slint-ui/declarative-programming] Moreover, the query `eat(X,jerry)` succeeds with the answer substitution `X=tom`.
[src:slint-ui/declarative-programming] Prolog executes programs top-down, using SLD resolution to reason backwards, reducing goals to subgoals.
[src:slint-ui/declarative-programming] In this example, it uses the last rule of the program to reduce the goal of answering the query `eat(X,jerry)` to the subgoals of first finding an X such that `big(X)` holds and then of showing that `small(jerry)` holds.
[src:slint-ui/declarative-programming] It repeatedly uses rules to further reduce subgoals to other subgoals, until it eventually succeeds in unifying all subgoals with facts in the program.
[src:slint-ui/declarative-programming] This backward reasoning, goal-reduction strategy treats rules in logic programs as procedures, and makes Prolog both a declarative and procedural programming language.
[src:slint-ui/declarative-programming] The broad range of Prolog applications is highlighted in the Year of Prolog Book, celebrating the 50 year anniversary of Prolog.
[src:slint-ui/declarative-programming] The origins of Datalog date back to the beginning of logic programming, but it was identified as a separate area around 1977.
[src:slint-ui/declarative-programming] Syntactically and semantically, it is a subset of Prolog.
[src:slint-ui/declarative-programming] But because it lacks compound terms, it is not Turing-complete.
[src:slint-ui/declarative-programming] Most Datalog systems execute programs bottom-up, using rules to reason forwards, deriving new facts from existing facts, and terminating when there are no new facts that can be derived, or when the derived facts unify with the query.
[src:slint-ui/declarative-programming] Datalog has been applied to such problems as data integration, information extraction, networking, security, cloud computing and machine learning.
[src:slint-ui/declarative-programming] Answer set programming (ASP) evolved in the late 1990s, based on the stable model (answer set) semantics of logic programming.
[src:slint-ui/declarative-programming] Like Datalog, it is a subset of Prolog; and, because it lacks compound terms, it is not Turing-complete.
[src:slint-ui/declarative-programming] Most implementations of ASP execute a program by first *grounding* the program, replacing all variables in rules by constants in all possible ways, and then using a propositional SAT solver, such as the DPLL algorithm to generate one or more models of the program.
[src:slint-ui/declarative-programming] Its applications are oriented towards solving difficult search problems and knowledge representation.
[src:slint-ui/opengl-es] The API is cross-language and multi-platform.
[src:slint-ui/opengl-es] OpenGL ES is managed by the non-profit technology consortium Khronos Group.
[src:slint-ui/opengl-es] Vulkan, a next-generation API from Khronos, is made for simpler high performance drivers for mobile and desktop devices.
[src:slint-ui/opengl-es] Several versions of the OpenGL ES specification now exist.
[src:slint-ui/opengl-es] OpenGL ES 1.0 is drawn up against the OpenGL 1.3 specification, OpenGL ES 1.1 is defined relative to the OpenGL 1.5 specification and OpenGL ES 2.0 is defined relative to the OpenGL 2.0 specification.
[src:slint-ui/opengl-es] This means that, for example, an application written for OpenGL ES 1.0 should be easily portable to the desktop OpenGL 1.3; as the OpenGL ES is a stripped-down version of the API, the reverse may or may not be true, depending on the particular features used.
[src:slint-ui/opengl-es] OpenGL ES comes with its own version of shading language (OpenGL ES SL), which is different from OpenGL SL.
[src:slint-ui/opengl-es] Version 1.0 and 1.1 both have *common* (CM) and *common lite* (CL) profiles, the difference being that the *common lite* profile only supports fixed-point instead of floating point data type support, whereas *common* supports both.
[src:slint-ui/opengl-es] OpenGL ES 1.0 was released publicly July 28, 2003.
[src:slint-ui/opengl-es] OpenGL ES 1.0 is based on the original OpenGL 1.3 API, with much functionality removed and a little bit added.
[src:slint-ui/opengl-es] One significant difference between OpenGL and OpenGL ES is that OpenGL ES removed the need to bracket OpenGL library calls with `glBegin` and `glEnd`.
[src:slint-ui/opengl-es] Other significant differences are that the calling semantics for primitive rendering functions were changed in favor of vertex arrays, and fixed-point data types were introduced for vertex coordinates.
[src:slint-ui/opengl-es] Attributes were also added to better support the computational abilities of embedded processors, which often lack a floating point unit (FPU).
[src:slint-ui/opengl-es] OpenGL ES 1.1 added features such as mandatory support for multitexture, better multitexture support (including combiners and dot product texture operations), automatic mipmap generation, vertex buffer objects, state queries, user clip planes, and greater control over point rendering.
[src:slint-ui/opengl-es] OpenGL ES 2.0 was publicly released in March 2007.
[src:slint-ui/opengl-es] It is roughly based on OpenGL 2.0, but it eliminates most of the fixed-function rendering pipeline in favor of a programmable one in a move similar to the transition from OpenGL 3.0 to 3.1.
[src:slint-ui/opengl-es] Control flow in shaders is generally limited to forward branching and to loops where the maximum number of iterations can easily be determined at compile time.
[src:slint-ui/opengl-es] Almost all rendering features of the transform and lighting stage, such as the specification of materials and light parameters formerly specified by the fixed-function API, are replaced by shaders written by the graphics programmer.
[src:slint-ui/opengl-es] As a result, OpenGL ES 2.0 is not backward compatible with OpenGL ES 1.1.
[src:slint-ui/opengl-es] Some incompatibilities between the desktop version of OpenGL and OpenGL ES 2.0 persisted until OpenGL 4.1, which added the `GL_ARB_ES2_compatibility` extension.
[src:slint-ui/opengl-es] The Khronos Group has written a document describing the differences between OpenGL ES 2.0 and ordinary OpenGL 2.0.
[src:slint-ui/opengl-es] The OpenGL ES 3.0 specification was publicly released in August 2012.
[src:slint-ui/opengl-es] It is backwards compatible with OpenGL ES 2.0, and partially compatible with WebGL 2.0, as WebGL 2.0 was designed to have a high degree of interoperability with OpenGL ES 3.0.
[src:slint-ui/opengl-es] The current version of the OpenGL ES 3.0 standard is 3.0.6, released in November 2019.
[src:slint-ui/opengl-es] The OpenGL ES 3.1 specification was publicly released in March 2014.
[src:slint-ui/opengl-es] OpenGL ES 3.1 is backward compatible with OpenGL ES 2.0 and 3.0, thus enabling applications to incrementally incorporate new features.
[src:slint-ui/opengl-es] The OpenGL ES 3.2 specification was publicly released in August 2015.
[src:slint-ui/opengl-es] Some more extensions are developed or in Development in Mesa for next OpenGL ES Version (see Mesamatrix).
[src:slint-ui/opengl-es] OpenGL ES 1.0 added an official 3D graphics API to the Android and Symbian OS v8.0a operating systems, as well as by QNX It is also supported by the PlayStation 3 as one of its official graphics APIs (the other one being low level *libgcm* library) with Nvidia's Cg in lieu of GLSL.
[src:slint-ui/opengl-es] The PlayStation 3 also includes several features of the 2.0 version of OpenGL ES.
[src:slint-ui/opengl-es] Android Extension Pack (AEP) is a set of OpenGL ES 3.1 extensions, all bundled into a single extension introduced by Google in 2014.
[src:slint-ui/opengl-es] This allows applications to use all of the features of the set of extensions, while only testing for the presence of a single one.
[src:slint-ui/opengl-es] The AEP was officially added to Android Lollipop to provide extra features like tessellation over what was officially in the GLES 3.1 revision.
[src:slint-ui/opengl-es] OpenGL ES 3.2 update is largely made up of the AEP additions, which are already present in desktop OpenGL.
[src:slint-ui/opengl-es] OpenGL ES 3.2, incorporating the Android Extension Pack (AEP), "boasts a small number of improvements over last year’s OpenGL ES 3.1.
[src:slint-ui/opengl-es] Both make use of similar features from the AEP.
[src:slint-ui/opengl-es] OpenGL ES (and OpenGL) was deprecated in Apple's operating systems in favour of its own proprietary Metal graphics API, but still worked in up to at least iOS 12.
[src:slint-ui/opengl-es] There is currently no plan for a new core version of OpenGL ES, as adoption of Vulkan has been deemed to displace it in embedded and mobile applications.
[src:slint-ui/opengl-es] Development of extensions to OpenGL ES continues as of 2017.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Rust supports multiple programming paradigms.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] It was influenced by ideas from functional programming, including immutability, higher-order functions, algebraic data types, and pattern matching.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] It also supports object-oriented programming via structs, enums, traits, and methods.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Rust enforces memory safety (i.e., that all references point to valid memory) without a conventional garbage collector; instead, memory safety errors and data races are prevented by the "borrow checker", which tracks the object lifetime of references at compile time.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Software developer Graydon Hoare created Rust in 2006 while working at Mozilla, which officially sponsored the project in 2009.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The first stable release, Rust 1.0, was published in May 2015.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The project has been sponsored by the Rust Foundation since February 2021.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Rust has been adopted by many software projects, especially web services and system software.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] It has been studied academically and has a growing community of developers.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Rust began as a personal project by Mozilla employee Graydon Hoare in 2006.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] According to *MIT Technology Review*, he started the project due to his frustration with a broken elevator in his apartment building whose software had crashed, and named the language after the group of fungi of the same name that is "over-engineered for survival".
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] During the time period between 2006 and 2009, Rust was not publicized to others at Mozilla and was written in Hoare's free time; Hoare began speaking about the language around 2009 after a small group at Mozilla became interested in the project.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Hoare cited languages from the 1970s, 1980s, and 1990s as influences — including CLU, BETA, Mesa, NIL, Erlang, Newsqueak, Napier, Hermes, Sather, Alef, and Limbo.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] During the early years, the Rust compiler was written in about 38,000 lines of OCaml.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Early Rust contained several features no longer present today, including explicit object-oriented programming via an `obj` keyword and a typestates system for variable state changes, such as going from uninitialized to initialized.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Mozilla officially sponsored the Rust project in 2009.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Brendan Eich and other executives, intrigued by the possibility of using Rust for a safe web browser engine, placed engineers on the project including Patrick Walton, Niko Matsakis, Felix Klock, and Manish Goregaokar.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] A conference room taken by the project developers was dubbed "the nerd cave," with a sign placed outside the door.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] During this time period, work had shifted from the initial OCaml compiler to a self-hosting compiler (*i.e.*, written in Rust) targeting LLVM.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The ownership system was in place by 2010.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The Rust logo was developed in 2011 based on a bicycle chainring.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Rust 0.1 became the first public release on January 20, 2012 for Windows, Linux, and MacOS.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The early 2010s witnessed increasing involvement from full-time engineers at Mozilla and open source volunteers outside Mozilla.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The years from 2012 to 2015 were marked by substantial changes to the Rust type system.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Memory management through the ownership system was gradually consolidated and expanded.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] By 2013, the garbage collector was rarely used, and was removed in favor of the ownership system.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Other features were removed in order to simplify the language, including typestates, the `pure` keyword, various specialized pointer types, and syntax support for channels.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] According to Steve Klabnik, Rust was influenced during this period by developers coming from C++ (e.g., low-level performance of features), scripting languages (e.g., Cargo and package management), and functional programming (e.g., type systems development).
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Graydon Hoare stepped down from Rust in 2013.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] After Hoare's departure, it evolved organically under a federated governance structure, with a "core team" of initially six people, and around 30-40 developers total across various other teams.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] A Request for Comments (RFC) process for new language features was added in March 2014.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The core team would grow to nine people by 2016 with over 1600 RFCs.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Dobb's Journal* in January 2014, while Rust was "widely viewed as a remarkably elegant language", adoption slowed because it radically changed from version to version.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Rust development at this time focused on finalizing features for version 1.0 so that it could begin promising backward compatibility.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Six years after Mozilla's sponsorship, Rust 1.0 was published and became the first stable release on May 15, 2015.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] A year later, the Rust compiler had accumulated over 1,400 contributors, and there were over 5,000 third-party libraries published on the Rust package management website Crates.io.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The development of the Servo browser engine continued in parallel with Rust, jointly funded by Mozilla and Samsung.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The teams behind the two projects worked in close collaboration; new features in Rust were tested out by the Servo team, and new features in Servo were used to give feedback back to the Rust team.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The first version of Servo was released in 2016.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The Firefox web browser shipped with Rust code as of 2016 (version 45), but components of Servo did not appear in Firefox until September 2017 (version 57) as part of the Gecko and Quantum projects.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Improvements were made to the Rust toolchain ecosystem during the years following 1.0 including Rustfmt, integrated development environment integration, and a regular compiler testing and release cycle.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Rust's community gained a code of conduct and an IRC chat for discussion.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The earliest known adoption outside of Mozilla was by individual projects at Samsung, Facebook (now Meta Platforms), Dropbox, and Tilde, Inc., the company behind ember.js.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Engineers cited performance, lack of a garbage collector, safety, and pleasantness of working in the language as reasons for the adoption.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Amazon developers cited a finding by Portuguese researchers that Rust code used less energy compared to similar code written in Java.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] In August 2020, Mozilla laid off 250 of its 1,000 employees worldwide, as part of a corporate restructuring caused by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The event raised concerns about the future of Rust.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] In the following week, the Rust Core Team acknowledged the severe impact of the layoffs and announced that plans for a Rust foundation were underway.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The first goal of the foundation would be to take ownership of all trademarks and domain names and to take financial responsibility for their costs.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] On February 8, 2021, the formation of the Rust Foundation was announced by five founding companies: Amazon Web Services, Google, Huawei, Microsoft, and Mozilla.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The foundation would provide financial support for Rust developers in the form of grants and server funding.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] In a blog post published on April 6, 2021, Google announced support for Rust within the Android Open Source Project as an alternative to C/C++.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] On November 22, 2021, the Moderation Team, which was responsible for enforcing the community code of conduct, announced their resignation "in protest of the Core Team placing themselves unaccountable to anyone but themselves".
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] In May 2022, members of the Rust leadership council posted a public response to the incident.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The Rust Foundation posted a draft for a new trademark policy on April 6, 2023, which resulted in widespread negative reactions from Rust users and contributors.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The trademark policy included rules for how the Rust logo and name could be used.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Rust's syntax is similar to that of C and C++, although many of its features were influenced by functional programming languages such as OCaml.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Hoare has described Rust as targeted at frustrated C++ developers.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Below is a "Hello, World!" program in Rust.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The `fn` keyword denotes a function, and the `println!` macro (see § Macros) prints the message to standard output.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Statements in Rust are separated by semicolons.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Variables in Rust are defined through the `let` keyword.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The example below assigns a value to the variable with name `foo` of type `i32` and outputs its value; the type annotation `: i32` can be omitted.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Variables are immutable by default, unless the `mut` keyword is added.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The following example uses `//`, which denotes the start of a comment.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Multiple `let` expressions can define multiple variables with the same name, known as variable shadowing.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing allows transforming variables without having to name the variables differently.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing is also possible for values of different types.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] A *block expression* is delimited by curly brackets.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] An `if` conditional expression executes code based on whether the given value is `true`.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] `else` can be used for when the value evaluates to `false`, and `else if` can be used for combining multiple expressions.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] `while` can be used to repeat a block of code while a condition is met.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] For loops in Rust loop over elements of a collection.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] `for` expressions work over any iterator type.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] In the above code, `4..=10` is a value of type `Range` which implements the `Iterator` trait.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The code within the curly braces is applied to each element returned by the iterator.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Iterators can be combined with functions over iterators like `map`, `filter`, and `sum`.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] More generally, the `loop` keyword allows repeating a portion of code until a `break` occurs.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] `break` may optionally exit the loop with a value.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] In the case of nested loops, labels denoted by `'label_name` can be used to break an outer loop rather than the innermost loop.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The `match` and `if let` expressions can be used for pattern matching.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Rust is strongly typed and statically typed, meaning that the types of all variables must be known at compilation time.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Assigning a value of a particular type to a differently typed variable causes a compilation error.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Type inference is used to determine the type of variables if unspecified.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The type `()`, called the "unit type" in Rust, is a concrete type that has exactly one value.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] It occupies no memory (as it represents the absence of value).
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] All functions that do not have an indicated return type implicitly return `()`.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] It is similar to `void` in other C-style languages; however, `void` denotes the absence of a type and cannot have any value.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The default integer type is `i32`, and the default floating point type is `f64`.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] If the type of a literal number is not explicitly provided, it is either inferred from the context or the default type is used.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Integer types in Rust are named based on the signedness and the number of bits the type takes.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] For example, `i32` is a signed integer that takes 32 bits of storage, whereas `u8` is unsigned and only takes 8 bits of storage.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] `isize` and `usize` take storage depending on the memory address bus width of the compilation target.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] For example, when building for 32-bit targets, both types will take up 32 bits of space.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals are in base-10, but different radices are supported with prefixes, for example, `0b11` for binary numbers, `0o567` for octals, and `0xDB` for hexadecimals.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals default to `i32` as its type.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Suffixes such as `4u32` can be used to explicitly set the type of a literal.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Byte literals such as `b'X'` are available to represent the ASCII value (as a `u8`) of a specific character.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The Boolean type is referred to as `bool` which can take a value of either `true` or `false`.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] A `char` takes up 32 bits of space and represents a Unicode scalar value: a Unicode codepoint that is not a surrogate.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] IEEE 754 floating point numbers are supported with `f32` for single precision floats and `f64` for double precision floats.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Compound types can contain multiple values.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Tuples are fixed-size lists that can contain values whose types can be different.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Arrays are fixed-size lists whose values are of the same type.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Rust's ownership system consists of rules that ensure memory safety without using a garbage collector.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] At compile time, each value must be attached to a variable called the *owner* of that value, and every value must have exactly one owner.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Values are moved between different owners through assignment or passing a value as a function parameter.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Values can also be *borrowed,* meaning they are temporarily passed to a different function before being returned to the owner.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Because of these ownership rules, Rust types are known as *affine types*, meaning each value may be used at most once.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] This enforces a form of software fault isolation as the owner of a value is solely responsible for its correctness and deallocation.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] When a value goes out of scope, it is *dropped* by running its destructor.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The destructor may be programmatically defined through implementing the `Drop` trait.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] This helps manage resources such as file handles, network sockets, and locks, since when objects are dropped, the resources associated with them are closed or released automatically.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Object lifetime refers to the period of time during which a reference is valid; that is, the time between the object creation and destruction.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] These *lifetimes* are implicitly associated with all Rust reference types.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] While often inferred, they can also be indicated explicitly with named lifetime parameters (often denoted `'a`, `'b`, and so on).
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] A value's lifetime in Rust is inferred from the set of locations in the source code (i.e., function, line, and column numbers) for which a variable is valid.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] For example, a reference to a local variable has a lifetime from the expression it is declared in up until the last use of it.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The borrow checker in the Rust compiler then enforces that references are only used in the locations of the source code where the associated lifetime is valid.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] In the example above, storing a reference to variable `x` in `r` is valid, as variable `x` has a longer lifetime (`'a`) than variable `r` (`'b`).
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Since the lifetime of the referenced variable (`'b`) is shorter than the lifetime of the variable holding the reference (`'a`), the borrow checker errors, preventing `x` from being used from outside its scope.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Lifetimes can be indicated using explicit *lifetime parameters* on function arguments.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] In the compiler, ownership and lifetimes work together to prevent memory safety issues such as dangling pointers.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] User-defined types are created with the `struct` or `enum` keywords.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The `struct` keyword is used to denote a record type that groups multiple related values.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] `enum`s can take on different variants at runtime, with their capabilities similar to algebraic data types found in functional programming languages.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Both records and enum variants can contain fields with different types.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Alternative names, or aliases, for the same type can be defined with the `type` keyword.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The `impl` keyword can define methods for a user-defined type.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Data and functions are defined separately.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Implementations fulfill a role similar to that of classes within other languages.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The Rust standard library defines and implements many widely used custom data types, including core data structures such as `Vec`, `Option`, and `HashMap`, as well as smart pointer types.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Rust provides a way to exclude most of the standard library using the attribute `#![no_std]`, for applications such as embedded devices.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Internally, the standard library is divided into three parts, `core`, `alloc`, and `std`, where `std` and `alloc` are excluded by `#![no_std]`.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Similarly, Rust's result type `Result<T, E>` holds either a successfully computed value (the `Ok` variant) or an error (the `Err` variant).
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Like `Option`, the use of `Result` means that the inner value cannot be used directly; programmers must use a `match` expression, syntactic sugar such as `?` (the "try" operator), or an explicit `unwrap` assertion to access it.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Both `Option` and `Result` are used throughout the standard library and are a fundamental part of Rust's explicit approach to handling errors and missing data.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The `&` and `&mut` reference types are guaranteed to not be null and point to valid memory.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The raw pointer types `*const` and `*mut` opt out of the safety guarantees, thus they may be null or invalid; however, it is impossible to dereference them unless the code is explicitly declared unsafe through the use of an `unsafe` block.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Unlike dereferencing, the creation of raw pointers is allowed inside safe Rust code.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Rust provides no implicit type conversion (coercion) between most primitive types.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] But, explicit type conversion (casting) can be performed using the `as` keyword.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Rust supports polymorphism through traits, generic functions, and trait objects.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The example above includes a method `is_zero` which provides a default implementation that may be overridden when implementing the trait.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] In the examples above, `Num: Zero` as well as `where Self: PartialEq` are trait bounds that constrain the type to only allow types that implement `Zero` or `PartialEq`.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Within a trait or impl, `Self` refers to the type that the code is implementing.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Generics can be used in functions to allow implementing a behavior for different types without repeating the same code (see bounded parametric polymorphism).
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Generic functions can be written in relation to other generics, without knowing the actual type.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] By default, traits use static dispatch: the compiler monomorphizes the function for each concrete type instance, yielding performance equivalent to type-specific code at the cost of longer compile times and larger binaries.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] When the exact type is not known at compile time, Rust provides trait objects `&dyn Trait` and `Box<dyn Trait>`.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Trait object calls use dynamic dispatch via a lookup table; a trait object is a "fat pointer" carrying both a data pointer and a method table pointer.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] This indirection adds a small runtime cost, but it keeps a single copy of the code and reduces binary size.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Only "object-safe" traits are eligible to be used as trait objects.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] This approach is similar to duck typing, where all data types that implement a given trait can be treated as functionally interchangeable.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] If an element in the list does not implement the `Display` trait, it will cause a compile-time error.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Memory and other resources are instead managed through the "resource acquisition is initialization" convention, with optional reference counting.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Rust provides deterministic management of resources, with very low overhead.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Values are allocated on the stack by default, and all dynamic allocations must be explicit.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The built-in reference types using the `&` symbol do not involve run-time reference counting.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The safety and validity of the underlying pointers are verified at compile time, preventing dangling pointers and other forms of undefined behavior.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Rust's type system separates shared, immutable references of the form `&T` from unique, mutable references of the form `&mut T`.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] A mutable reference can be coerced to an immutable reference, but not vice versa.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Rust's memory safety checks (See #Safety) may be circumvented through the use of `unsafe` blocks.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] This allows programmers to dereference arbitrary raw pointers, call external code, or perform other low-level functionality not allowed by safe Rust.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Some low-level functionality enabled in this way includes volatile memory access, architecture-specific intrinsics, type punning, and inline assembly.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Unsafe code is needed, for example, in the implementation of data structures.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] A frequently cited example is that it is difficult or impossible to implement doubly linked lists in safe Rust.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Programmers using unsafe Rust are considered responsible for upholding Rust's memory and type safety requirements, for example, that no two mutable references exist pointing to the same location.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] If programmers write code that violates these requirements, this results in undefined behavior.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The Rust documentation includes a list of behaviors considered undefined, including accessing dangling or misaligned pointers, or breaking the aliasing rules for references.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Macros allow the generation and transformation of Rust code to reduce repetition.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Macros come in two forms, with *declarative macros* defined through `macro_rules!`, and *procedural macros*, which are defined in separate crates.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] A declarative macro (also called a "macro by example") is a macro, defined using the `macro_rules!` keyword, that uses pattern matching to determine its expansion.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] In this example, the macro named `sum` is defined using the form `macro_rules! sum {` `(...) => { ... } }`.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The first part inside the parentheses of the definition, the macro pattern `( $initial:expr $(, $expr:expr )* $(,)? )` specifies the structure of input it can take.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Here, `$initial:expr` represents the first expression, while `$(, $expr:expr )*` means there can be zero or more additional comma-separated expressions after it.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The trailing `$(,)?` allows the caller to optionally include a final comma without causing an error.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The second part, after the arrow `=>`, describes what code will be generated when the macro is invoked.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] In this case, `$initial $(+ $expr)*` means that the generated code will start with the first expression, followed by a `+` and each of the additional expressions in sequence.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The `*` again means "repeat this pattern zero or more times".
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] This means, when the macro is later called in line 8, as `sum!(1, 2, 3)`, the macro will resolve to `1 + 2 + 3` representing the addition of all of the passed expressions.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Procedural macros are Rust functions that run and modify the compiler's input token stream, before any other components are compiled.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] They are generally more flexible than declarative macros, but are more difficult to maintain due to their complexity.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Rust supports the creation of foreign function interfaces (FFI) through the `extern` keyword.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] A function that uses the C calling convention can be written using `extern "C" fn`.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The `#[repr(C)]` attribute enables deterministic memory layouts for `struct`s and `enum`s for use across FFI boundaries.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] External libraries such as `bindgen` and `cxx` can generate Rust bindings for C/C++.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Safety properties guaranteed by Rust include memory safety, type safety, and data race freedom.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] As described above, these guarantees can be circumvented by using the `unsafe` keyword.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Memory safety includes the absence of dereferences to null, dangling, and misaligned pointers, and the absence of buffer overflows and double free errors.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Memory leaks may occur as a result of creating reference-counted pointers that point at each other (a reference cycle) or can be deliberately created through calling `Box::leak`.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The Rust ecosystem includes its compiler, its standard library, and additional components for software development.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Component installation is typically managed by `rustup`, a Rust toolchain installer developed by the Rust project.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The Rust compiler, `rustc`, compiles Rust code into binaries.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] First, the compiler parses the source code into an AST.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The compiler backend is then invoked as a subcomponent to apply optimizations and translate the resulting IR into object code.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Finally, a linker is used to combine the object(s) into a single executable image.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] rustc uses LLVM as its compiler backend by default, but it also supports using alternative backends such as GCC and Cranelift.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The intention of those alternative backends is to increase platform coverage of Rust or to improve compilation times.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Cargo is Rust's build system and package manager.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] It downloads, compiles, distributes, and uploads packages—called *crates*—that are maintained in an official registry.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] It also acts as a front-end for Clippy and other Rust components.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] By default, Cargo sources its dependencies from the user-contributed registry *crates.io*, but Git repositories, crates in the local filesystem, and other external sources can also be specified as dependencies.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Cargo supports reproducible builds through two metadata files: Cargo.toml and Cargo.lock.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Cargo.toml declares each package used and their version requirements.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Cargo.lock is generated automatically during dependency resolution and records exact versions of all dependencies, including transitive dependencies.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] It formats whitespace and indentation to produce code in accordance with a common style, unless otherwise specified.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] It can be invoked as a standalone program or from a Rust project through Cargo.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Clippy is Rust's built-in linting tool to improve the correctness, performance, and readability of Rust code.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Following Rust 1.0, new features are developed in *nightly* versions, which are released daily.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] During each six-week release cycle, changes to nightly versions are released to beta, while changes from the previous beta version are released to a new stable version.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Every two or three years, a new "edition" is produced.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Editions are released to allow making limited breaking changes, such as promoting `await` to a keyword to support async/await features.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Crates targeting different editions can interoperate with each other, so a crate can upgrade to a new edition even if its callers or its dependencies still target older editions.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Migration to a new edition can be assisted with automated tooling.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Since it performs no garbage collection, Rust is often faster than other memory-safe languages.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Most of Rust's memory safety guarantees impose no runtime overhead, with the notable exception of array indexing which is checked at runtime by default.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The performance impact of array indexing bounds checks varies, but can be significant in some cases.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Many of Rust's features are so-called *zero-cost abstractions*, meaning they are optimized away at compile time and incur no runtime penalty.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The ownership and borrowing system permits zero-copy implementations for some performance-sensitive tasks, such as parsing.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Static dispatch is used by default to eliminate method calls, except for methods called on dynamic trait objects.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The compiler uses inline expansion to eliminate function calls and statically dispatched method invocations.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Unlike C and C++, Rust allows the compiler to reorder struct and enum elements unless a `#[repr(C)]` representation attribute is applied.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] This allows the compiler to produce more efficient code in some cases.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Performance improvements in LLVM carry over to Rust.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] In web services, OpenDNS, a DNS resolution service owned by Cisco, uses Rust internally.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Amazon Web Services uses Rust in "performance-sensitive components" of services.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] In 2019, AWS open-sourced Firecracker, a virtualization solution primarily written in Rust.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Microsoft Azure IoT Edge, a platform used to run Azure services on IoT devices, has components implemented in Rust.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Microsoft also uses Rust to run containerized modules with WebAssembly and Kubernetes.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Cloudflare, a company providing content delivery network services, used Rust to build a new web proxy named Pingora for increased performance and efficiency.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The npm package manager used Rust for its production authentication service in 2019.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] In operating systems, the Linux kernel began introducing experimental support for Rust code in Version 6.1 in late 2022, as part of the Rust for Linux project.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The first drivers written in Rust were included in version 6.8.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] In 2025, kernel developers at the Linux Kernel Developers Summit determined the project to be a success, and Rust usage for kernel code will no longer be considered experimental.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The Android developers used Rust in 2021 to rewrite existing components.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Microsoft has rewritten parts of Windows in Rust.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The r9 project aims to re-implement Plan 9 from Bell Labs in Rust.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Rust has also been used in the development of new operating systems such as Redox, a "Unix-like" operating system and microkernel, Theseus, an experimental operating system with modular state management, and most of Fuchsia.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Rust is used for command-line tools and operating system components such as stratisd, a file system manager and COSMIC, a desktop environment by System76.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] In web development, Deno, a secure runtime for JavaScript and TypeScript, is built on top of V8 using Rust and Tokio.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Other notable adoptions in this space include Ruffle, an open-source SWF emulator, and Polkadot, an open source blockchain and cryptocurrency platform.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Components from the Servo browser engine (funded by Mozilla and Samsung) were incorporated in the Gecko browser engine underlying Firefox.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] In January 2023, Google (Alphabet) announced support for using third party Rust libraries in Chromium.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] In other uses, Discord, an instant messaging software company, rewrote parts of its system in Rust for increased performance in 2020.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] In the same year, Dropbox announced that its file synchronization had been rewritten in Rust.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Facebook (Meta) used Rust to redesign its system that manages source code for internal projects.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] In the 2025 Stack Overflow Developer Survey, 14.8% of respondents had recently done extensive development in Rust.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The survey named Rust the "most admired programming language" annually from 2016 to 2025 (inclusive), as measured by the number of existing developers interested in continuing to work in the language.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] In 2025, 29.2% of developers not currently working in Rust expressed an interest in doing so.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Rust's safety and performance have been investigated in programming languages research.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] In other fields, a journal article published to *Proceedings of the International Astronomical Union* used Rust to simulate multi-planet systems.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] An article published in *Nature* shared stories of bioinformaticians using Rust.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Both articles cited Rust's performance and safety as advantages, and the learning curve as being a primary drawback to Rust adoption.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The 2025 DARPA project TRACTOR aims to automatically translate C to Rust using techniques such as static analysis, dynamic analysis, and large language models.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] According to the *MIT Technology Review*, the Rust community has been seen as "unusually friendly" to newcomers and particularly attracted people from the queer community, partly due to its code of conduct.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] Inclusiveness has been cited as an important factor for some Rust developers.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The official Rust blog collects and publishes demographic data each year.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The **Rust Foundation** is a non-profit membership organization incorporated in United States; it manages the Rust trademark, infrastructure, and assets.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] It was established on February 8, 2021, with five founding corporate members (Amazon Web Services, Huawei, Google, Microsoft, and Mozilla).
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The foundation's board was chaired by Shane Miller, with Ashley Williams as interim executive director.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] In late 2021, Rebecca Rumbul became executive director and CEO.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The Rust project is maintained by 8 top-level *teams* as of November 2025: the leadership council, compiler team, dev tools team, infrastructure team, language team, launching pad, library team, and moderation team.
[src:slint-ui/rust-programming-language] The leadership council oversees the project and is formed by representatives among the other teams.
[src:slint-ui/software-framework] A **software framework** is software that provides reusable, generic functionality which developers can extend or customize to create complete solutions.
[src:slint-ui/software-framework] It offers an abstraction layer over lower-level code and infrastructure, allowing developers to focus on implementing business logic rather than building common functionality from scratch.
[src:slint-ui/software-framework] Generally, a framework is intended to enhance productivity by allowing developers to focus on satisfying business requirements rather than reimplementing generic functionality.
[src:slint-ui/software-framework] Frameworks often include support programs, compilers, software development kits, code libraries, toolsets, and APIs that integrate various components within a larger software platform or environment.
[src:slint-ui/software-framework] Unlike a library, where user code controls the program's control flow, a framework implements inversion of control by dictating the overall structure and calling user code at predefined extension points (e.g., through template methods or hooks).
[src:slint-ui/software-framework] Frameworks also provide default behaviours that work out-of-the-box, structured mechanisms for extensibility, and a fixed core that accepts extensions (e.g., plugins or subclasses) without direct modification.
[src:slint-ui/software-framework] A framework differs from an application that can be extended—such as a web browser via an extension or a video game via a mod—in that it is intentionally incomplete scaffolding designed to be completed through its extension points while following specific architectural patterns.
[src:slint-ui/software-framework] For example, a team using a web framework to develop a banking website can focus on writing banking business logic rather than handling low-level details like web request processing or state management.
[src:slint-ui/software-framework] According to Pree, software frameworks consist of *frozen spots* and *hot spots*.
[src:slint-ui/software-framework] *Frozen spots* define the overall architecture of a software system, that is to say its basic components and the relationships between them.
[src:slint-ui/software-framework] These remain unchanged (frozen) in any instantiation of the application framework.
[src:slint-ui/software-framework] *Hot spots* represent the parts where the programmers using the framework add their own code to add the functionality specific to their own project.
[src:slint-ui/software-framework] The necessary functionality can be implemented by using the Template Method Pattern in which the *frozen spots* are known as invariant methods and the *hot spots* are known as variant or hook methods.
[src:slint-ui/software-framework] The invariant methods in the superclass provide default behaviour while the hook methods in each subclass provide custom behaviour.
[src:slint-ui/software-framework] When developing a concrete software system with a software framework, developers utilize the hot spots according to the specific needs and requirements of the system.
[src:slint-ui/software-framework] Software frameworks rely on the Hollywood Principle: "Don't call us, we'll call you." This means that the user-defined classes (for example, new subclasses) receive messages from the predefined framework classes.
[src:slint-ui/software-framework] Developers usually handle this by implementing superclass abstract methods.
[src:slint-ui/software-framework] One potential downside of using a framework is that it adds to the size of a program, a phenomenon termed code bloat.
[src:slint-ui/software-framework] This can be exacerbated by using multiple, sometimes competing, frameworks in the same codebase.
[src:slint-ui/software-framework] Learning how to use a framework can be substantial.
[src:slint-ui/software-framework] The intended efficiencies of using the framework may be outweighed by the cost to learn it, especially for a framework that is new to the development staff.
[src:slint-ui/software-framework] However, once a framework is learned, development team speed may increase for future work.
[src:slint-ui/software-framework] Some claim that the most effective frameworks evolve from re-factoring an existing solution, such as a generic one-size-fits-all framework developed by third parties for general purposes, rather than from green-field development.
[src:slint-ui/widget-toolkit] A **widget toolkit**, **widget library**, **GUI toolkit**, **GUI framework**, **UI framework**, or **UX library** is a library or a collection of libraries containing a set of graphical control elements (called *widgets*) used to construct the graphical user interface (GUI) of programs.
[src:slint-ui/widget-toolkit] Most widget toolkits additionally include their own rendering engine.
[src:slint-ui/widget-toolkit] This engine can be specific to a certain operating system or windowing system or contain back-ends to interface with multiple ones and also with rendering APIs such as OpenGL, OpenVG, or EGL.
[src:slint-ui/widget-toolkit] The look and feel of the graphical control elements can be hard-coded or decoupled, allowing the graphical control elements to be themed/skinned.
[src:slint-ui/widget-toolkit] Some toolkits may be used from other languages by employing language bindings.
[src:slint-ui/widget-toolkit] Graphical user interface builders such as e.g.
[src:slint-ui/widget-toolkit] Glade Interface Designer facilitate the authoring of GUIs in a WYSIWYG manner employing a user interface markup language such as in this case GtkBuilder.
[src:slint-ui/widget-toolkit] The GUI of a program is commonly constructed in a cascading manner, with graphical control elements being added directly to on top of one another.
[src:slint-ui/widget-toolkit] Most widget toolkits use event-driven programming as a model for interaction.
[src:slint-ui/widget-toolkit] The toolkit handles user events, for example when the user clicks on a button.
[src:slint-ui/widget-toolkit] When an event is detected, it is passed on to the application where it is dealt with.
[src:slint-ui/widget-toolkit] The design of those toolkits has been criticized for promoting an oversimplified model of event-action, leading programmers to create error-prone, difficult to extend and excessively complex application code.
[src:slint-ui/widget-toolkit] Finite-state machines and hierarchical state machines have been proposed as high-level models to represent the interactive state changes for reactive programs.
[src:slint-ui/widget-toolkit] A window is considered to be a graphical control element.
[src:slint-ui/widget-toolkit] In some windowing systems, windows are added directly to the scene graph (canvas) by the window manager, and can be stacked and layered on top of each other through various means.
[src:slint-ui/widget-toolkit] Each window is associated with a particular application which controls the widgets added to its canvas, which can be watched and modified by their associated applications.
